## Code expl

Awesome—this is a clean Ops panel! I’ll walk you through it section by section, explaining what each line/block does and why it’s there, plus a few gotchas and improvement tips.

1) Imports
import React from 'react';
import { LogOut, Database, RefreshCw, CheckCircle, XCircle, Clock } from 'lucide-react';


React is required to author JSX (even with the new JSX transform it’s fine to keep).

Icons come from lucide-react and are just React components you can render like <LogOut />.

2) Component signature + props
const OpsDashboard = ({ navigate }) => {


You’re not using react-router here; instead the parent (App.js) passes a navigate(pageKey) function.

So navigate('landing') triggers your app’s manual page switch.

3) Mock user + logout
const user = { name: 'Ramesh', role: 'operations' };
const logout = () => {
  navigate('landing');
};


user is just display info for the header.

logout() uses your custom navigate to bounce back to the landing page.

4) Mock sync jobs (display data)
const syncJobs = [
  { id: 1, source: 'AWS S3 - Finance', status: 'completed', progress: 100, files: 12, time: '2 mins ago' },
  { id: 2, source: 'Google Cloud - Reports', status: 'in-progress', progress: 67, files: 8, time: 'Running' },
  { id: 3, source: 'Azure Blob - Analytics', status: 'pending', progress: 0, files: 15, time: 'Scheduled' },
  { id: 4, source: 'Local Storage - Archive', status: 'failed', progress: 45, files: 5, time: '10 mins ago' },
];


Array of jobs drives the “Recent Sync Operations” list.

Each object controls: which icon/badge to show, progress bar width, and action buttons.

5) Status helpers (icon + badge)
const getStatusIcon = (status) => {
  const base = { width: 20, height: 20 };
  switch (status) {
    case 'completed':  return <CheckCircle style={{ ...base, color: '#38D200' }} />;
    case 'in-progress':return <RefreshCw   style={{ ...base, color: '#0473EA' }} className="spin" />;
    case 'failed':     return <XCircle     style={{ ...base, color: '#dc2626' }} />;
    default:           return <Clock       style={{ ...base, color: '#6b7280' }} />;
  }
};


Returns the appropriate icon for each job status.

For in-progress it adds className="spin" — you define the CSS animation later.

const getStatusBadge = (status) => {
  const styles = {
    base: { padding: '3px 10px', borderRadius: 999, fontSize: 12, fontWeight: 600, textTransform: 'capitalize' },
    completed:   { background: '#38D200', color: '#fff' },
    'in-progress': { background: '#0473EA', color: '#fff' },
    failed:      { background: '#dc2626', color: '#fff' },
    pending:     { background: '#9ca3af', color: '#fff' },
  };
  return <span style={{ ...styles.base, ...(styles[status] || styles.pending) }}>{status}</span>;
};


Returns a colored pill for the status.

Uses a base style + merges the matching status style (fallback to “pending”).

6) Reusable style objects
const button = {
  base: { display:'inline-flex', alignItems:'center', gap:8, padding:'8px 12px', borderRadius:8, border:'1px solid #e5e7eb', background:'#fff', cursor:'pointer', fontWeight:600 },
  primary: { border:'none', background:'#0473EA', color:'#fff' },
};


button.base = neutral button; button.primary = call-to-action (blue).

You later combine them with spread: { ...button.base, ...button.primary }.

const card = {
  container: { border:'1px solid #e5e7eb', borderRadius:12, background:'#fff' },
  header: { padding:16, borderBottom:'1px solid #f3f4f6' },
  title:  { margin:0, fontSize:18 },
  desc:   { margin:'4px 0 0', color:'#6b7280', fontSize:14 },
  content:{ padding:16 },
};


Shared “card” styles for the sections: “Storage Connections” and “Recent Sync Operations”.

7) Progress bar renderer
const progressBar = (value, status) => {
  const green = '#38D200';
  const blue  = '#0473EA';

  return (
    <div style={{
      width:'100%', height:8, borderRadius:999, display:'flex', overflow:'hidden', background: blue,
    }}>
      <div style={{ width:`${value}%`, background: green, transition:'width 0.3s ease' }} />
    </div>
  );
};


Container is blue (remaining segment).

Inner div width = value% in green (completed segment).

Simple, performant, and CSS-only.

8) Top-level layout
return (
  <div style={{ minHeight: '100vh', background: '#f9fafb' }}>


Full-page container with a light gray background.

